Practical Machine Learning Assignment

Introduction

Using devices such as Jawbone Up, Nike FuelBand, and Fitbit it is now possible to collect a large amount of data about personal activity relatively inexpensively. These type of devices are part of the quantified self movement – a group of enthusiasts who take measurements about themselves regularly to improve their health, to find patterns in their behavior, or because they are tech geeks. One thing that people regularly do is quantify how much of a particular activity they do, but they rarely quantify how well they do it. In this project, your goal will be to use data from accelerometers on the belt, forearm, arm, and dumbell of 6 participants. They were asked to perform barbell lifts correctly and incorrectly in 5 different ways. More information is available from the website here: http://groupware.les.inf.puc-rio.br/har (see the section on the Weight Lifting Exercise Dataset).

A number of variables have a high percentage of missing cases. These are omitted:

omit <- (apply(training,2,function(x) sum(is.na(x))/length(x))>.9)
training2 <- training[,omit==FALSE]

Boxplot of the remaining ~60 variables:

training2.melt <- melt(training2[,-c(1:6,60)])
## No id variables; using all as measure variables
box.plot <- ggplot(data = training2.melt,aes(x=variable,y=value))+
  geom_boxplot() + coord_flip()
box.plot

Correlation amongst the variables:

cor.mat <- round(cor(training2[,-c(1:6,60)]),2)
corrplot(cor.mat,method = "circle",type = "lower",tl.cex = .6,order = "FPC"
         ,tl.col = "black")

Modeling & Results

The training dataset is divided into two parts for training and testing purposes:

trn <- createDataPartition(y=training2$classe,p = .7, list=F)
trainset <- training2[trn,]
testset <- training2[-trn,]

The first 10 variables based on the above method are selected for further modeling.

trainset2 <- (trainset[,-c(1:6)])
rf.imp <- randomForest(as.factor(classe)~.,data = trainset2,
                       importance = TRUE,ntree = 100)
imp <- data.frame("var"=row.names(rf.imp$importance),
                  "vls"=rf.imp$importance[,"MeanDecreaseGini"],
                  row.names = NULL)
imp <- imp[order(imp$vls,decreasing = T),]
imp[1:10,]
##                  var      vls
## 1         num_window 965.3683
## 2          roll_belt 765.2250
## 4           yaw_belt 595.4574
## 40 magnet_dumbbell_z 516.2736
## 39 magnet_dumbbell_y 477.8723
## 42     pitch_forearm 469.2052
## 3         pitch_belt 451.4979
## 41      roll_forearm 357.3151
## 11      accel_belt_z 328.7028
## 38 magnet_dumbbell_x 297.8064
varn <- as.character(imp[1:10,1])

A random forest model is run for the training set:

set.seed(42)
rf <- train(as.factor(classe)~.,data=trainset[,c(varn,"classe")],
            method = "rf",
            trControl =trainControl(method = "cv",
                                      number=3,repeats=1,
                                      verboseIter = F))

The results are given below. The accuracy of the model is pretty high:

rf.predict <- predict(rf,newdata = testset[,varn])
rf.conmat <- confusionMatrix(rf.predict,testset$classe)
rf.conmat
